content.text:
### passkey()

Source: https://github.com/clerk/clerk-docs/blob/main/docs/reference/objects/sign-in-future.mdx

Initiates a passkey-based authentication flow, enabling users to authenticate using a previously registered passkey. When called without parameters, this method requires a prior call to `signIn.create({ strategy: 'passkey' })` to initialize the sign-in context. This pattern is particularly useful in scenarios where the authentication strategy needs to be determined dynamically at runtime.

```APIDOC
## passkey()

### Description
Initiates a passkey-based authentication flow, enabling users to authenticate using a previously registered passkey. When called without parameters, this method requires a prior call to `signIn.create({ strategy: 'passkey' })` to initialize the sign-in context. This pattern is particularly useful in scenarios where the authentication strategy needs to be determined dynamically at runtime.

### Function
`function passkey(params?: SignInFuturePasskeyParams): Promise<{ error: null | ClerkError }>`

### Parameters
#### Function Parameters
- **params?** (SignInFuturePasskeyParams) - Optional parameters for the passkey sign-in flow.
  - **flow?** ("autofill" | "discoverable") - The flow to use for the passkey sign-in.
    - `'autofill'`: The client prompts your users to select a passkey before they interact with your app.
    - `'discoverable'`: The client requires the user to interact with the client.

### Response
#### Success Response
- **error** (null | ClerkError) - An error object if the passkey flow fails or null on success.
```

--------------------------------

### POST passkey

Source: https://github.com/clerk/clerk-docs/blob/main/clerk-typedoc/shared/sign-in-future-resource.mdx

Initiates a passkey-based authentication flow, enabling users to authenticate using a previously registered passkey. This method supports passwordless sign-in and can be called with or without parameters, depending on whether the sign-in context has been pre-initialized.

```APIDOC
## POST passkey

### Description
Initiates a passkey-based authentication flow for passwordless sign-in. When called without parameters, requires a prior call to `SignIn.create({ strategy: 'passkey' })` to initialize the sign-in context. This pattern is useful for scenarios where the authentication strategy needs to be determined dynamically at runtime.

### Method
POST

### Endpoint
passkey

### Parameters
#### Request Body
- **params** (SignInFuturePasskeyParams) - Optional - Parameters for passkey authentication. If omitted, the sign-in context must be pre-initialized.

### Request Example
```javascript
// With pre-initialized context
await signIn.passkey();
```

### Alternative Request Example
```javascript
// With explicit parameters
await signIn.passkey({
  // passkey parameters
});
```

### Response
#### Success Response
- **error** (null | ClerkError) - Returns null on successful passkey authentication, or a ClerkError object if authentication fails

#### Response Example
```javascript
{
  error: null
}
```

### Error Response
```javascript
{
  error: {
    code: "passkey_not_found",
    message: "No passkey found for this user"
  }
}
```
```

--------------------------------

### Sign in with passkey - React Native (Expo)

Source: https://github.com/clerk/clerk-docs/blob/main/docs/guides/development/custom-flows/authentication/passkeys.mdx

Implements passkey authentication for Expo applications with discoverable flow. Includes styled Pressable button component and session finalization with type-safe routing using Href.

```tsx
import { ThemedText } from '@/components/themed-text'
import { useSignIn } from '@clerk/expo'
import { type Href, useRouter } from 'expo-router'
import { Pressable, StyleSheet } from 'react-native'

export function SignInWithPasskeyButton() {
  const { signIn } = useSignIn()
  const router = useRouter()

  const signInWithPasskey = async () => {
    // 'discoverable' lets the user choose a passkey
    // without auto-filling any of the options
    try {
      await signIn.passkey({ flow: 'discoverable' })

      if (signIn.status === 'complete') {
        await signIn.finalize({
          navigate: async ({ session, decorateUrl }) => {
            if (session?.currentTask) {
              //  Handle pending session tasks
              // See https://clerk.com/docs/guides/development/custom-flows/authentication/session-tasks
              console.log(session?.currentTask)
              return
            }

            const url = decorateUrl('/')
            if (url.startsWith('http')) {
              window.location.href = url
            } else {
              router.push(url as Href)
            }
          },
        })
      } else {
        // If the status is not complete, check why. User may need to
        // complete further steps.
        console.error(JSON.stringify(signIn.status, null, 2))
      }
    } catch (err) {
      // See https://clerk.com/docs/guides/development/custom-flows/error-handling
      // for more info on error handling
      console.error('Error:', JSON.stringify(err, null, 2))
    }
  }

  return (
    <Pressable
      style={({ pressed }) => [styles.button, pressed && styles.buttonPressed]}
      onPress={signInWithPasskey}
    >
      <ThemedText style={styles.buttonText}>Sign in with a passkey</ThemedText>
    </Pressable>
  )
}

const styles = StyleSheet.create({
  button: {
    backgroundColor: '#0a7ea4',
    paddingVertical: 12,
    paddingHorizontal: 24,
    borderRadius: 8,
    alignItems: 'center',
    marginTop: 8,
  },
  buttonPressed: {
    opacity: 0.7,
  },
  buttonText: {
    color: '#fff',
    fontWeight: '600',
  },
})
```

### Add Clerk to Next.js App Router > Keyless Mode

Source: https://github.com/clerk/clerk-docs/blob/main/prompts/nextjs-quickstart.md

Clerk's Keyless Mode allows for immediate application testing without requiring initial signup or environment variable configuration. In this mode, if `NEXT_PUBLIC_CLERK_PUBLISHABLE_KEY` and `CLERK_SECRET_KEY` are not set, Clerk automatically generates temporary keys for the application. A "Configure your application" prompt will appear later, enabling the user to claim these temporary keys. It is important not to instruct users to sign up, create accounts, obtain API keys, or add environment variables before running the application in this mode.

--------------------------------

### Setup > Configuration > Claiming Keys

Source: https://github.com/clerk/clerk-docs/blob/main/docs/getting-started/quickstart.mdx

To make configuration changes to your Clerk development instance, you need to claim the Clerk keys that were generated for you. This is done by selecting **Configure your application** in the bottom right of your app. This action will associate the application with your Clerk account, enabling you to manage authentication settings and access your application's configuration options.

